{"id":"1512.07603","submitter":"James Tan","authors":"James P.L. Tan","title":"Symmetric and Asymmetric Tendencies in Stable Complex Systems","comments":"21 pages, 5 figures. v2: Corrected typos in abstract. v3: major\n  revision. v4: communicated to Sci Rep","journal-ref":"Sci. Rep. 6 (2016) 31762","doi":"10.1038/srep31762","report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.PE cond-mat.dis-nn cond-mat.stat-mech nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A commonly used approach to study stability in a complex system is by\nanalyzing the Jacobian matrix at an equilibrium point of a dynamical system.\nThe equilibrium point is stable if all eigenvalues have negative real parts.\nHere, by obtaining eigenvalue bounds of the Jacobian, we show that stable\ncomplex systems will favor mutualistic and competitive relationships that are\nasymmetrical (non-reciprocative) and trophic relationships that are symmetrical\n(reciprocative). Additionally, we define a measure called the interdependence\ndiversity that quantifies how distributed the dependencies are between the\ndynamical variables in the system. We find that increasing interdependence\ndiversity has a destabilizing effect on the equilibrium point, and the effect\nis greater for trophic relationships than for mutualistic and competitive\nrelationships. These predictions are consistent with empirical observations in\necology. More importantly, our findings suggest stabilization algorithms that\ncan apply very generally to a variety of complex systems.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 23 Dec 2015 19:56:19 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 24 Dec 2015 12:28:50 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 25 Apr 2016 15:40:38 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 23 Aug 2016 01:43:20 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-09-02"}
